pull_request.title: New ChatView: Support incoming updates of messages
pull_request.body:
Use `kMonalUpdatedMessageNotice` for message corrections and MUC message reflections, instead of using `kMonalNewMessageNotice`.

I added observing of this new notification in all the places that are observing `kMonalNewMessageNotice`, except for `MonalAppDelegate`.
I think that's not needed because message updates don't cause the unread counter to be changed.

Also, I'm not sure observing the new notification in `MLContact` is strictly necessary, but it's not harmful.


On a semi-related note, you once said that when posting notifications, `MLNotificationQueue` should always be used (as opposed to `NSNotificationCenter`)
It turns out there are some places in the code base that use `NSNotificationCenter` for posting notifications.
See them with `grep --color=auto -in 'NotificationCenter.*post' Monal/Classes/*.{m,swift}`
Should I use `MLNotificationQueue` in these places?
(The `CFNotificationCenter` ones should remain)

issue.title: Fix QueryJob total_rows attribute error
issue.body:
# Fix QueryJob total_rows attribute error ## Summary This PR fixes a critical `AttributeError` that occurs when the BigQuery API returns a `QueryJob` object without the `total_rows` attribute. The error `'QueryJob' object has no attribute 'total_rows'` was causing the application to crash when users asked questions like "how many republicans are there". **Root Cause:** The BigQuery `QueryJob` object doesn't always populate the `total_rows` attribute, particularly for certain query types (like COUNT queries) or under specific conditions. The code was attempting to access this attribute directly, causing an AttributeError. **Fix:** Changed from direct attribute access `query_job.total_rows` to safe access using `getattr(query_job, 'total_rows', None)`, which returns None if the attribute doesn't exist rather than raising an exception. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Critical**: Test end-to-end with actual BigQuery queries that return results (not just permission errors) to verify the fix works and doesn't break normal functionality - [ ] **High**: Verify truncation detection still works correctly when `total_rows` is available vs when it's None - [ ] **Medium**: Test various query types (SELECT, COUNT, aggregations, complex queries) to ensure consistent behavior across different BigQuery response patterns **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Run the agent CLI with COUNT queries: "how many republicans are there" 2. Run regular SELECT queries to ensure truncation detection still works 3. Try various query patterns to verify no regression in functionality --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD CLI["app_cli.py"]:::context --> Agent["agent.py"]:::context Agent --> BQTool["bigquery_tool.py"]:::minor-edit BQTool --> BQClient["BigQuery Client"]:::context BQTool --> TotalRowsFix["Safe total_rows access
using getattr()"]:::minor-edit TotalRowsFix --> TruncationLogic["Truncation Detection

Full end-to-end testing with successful queries is needed. - **Previous PR Issue**: This fix was supposedly included in PR #57 which shows as "Merged", but the fix didn't make it to main properly, suggesting there may have been a merge issue. - **Change Impact**: Minimal code change (2 lines) but affects a critical path in query result processing. **Session Info**: Requested by Greg (gregtusar@gmail.com) **Link to Devin run**: https://app.devin.ai/sessions/70ba3ae6fc8d46b48eb248b1e5354fd1

issue.title: solfuzzer terminates with a crash on inputs containing invalid UTF-8 (mild obstacle to fuzzing)
issue.body:
Given any .sol input from standard input that contains invalid UTF-8 (which will frequently be produced by byte-mutating fuzzers like AFL), solfuzzer fails like this:

```
Testing compiler with optimizer.
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'nlohmann::json_abi_v3_11_3::detail::type_error'
  what():  [json.exception.type_error.316] invalid UTF-8 byte at index 35: 0x80
Aborted
```

This looks like a crash to the fuzzer, so produces lots of spurious crashes and an annoying burden for triage.  The solc executable does not crash on such inputs, as far as I can see.  This isn't a major problem, fuzzing still works, but it definitely imposes a cost (of 9 million executions of solfuzzer in one fuzzing run, over 3 million have been crashes due to this UTF-8 issue, and with a larger starting corpus especially the crash set is composed of a huge number of ways to reach this uninteresting non-bug crash).

This is on the latest solc/solidity (0.8.24 github main branch)

## Steps to Reproduce

Just run solfuzzer on an input like:

```
contract test {
    f\200^@ction g() pu\203lic { f(); }
}
```

`build/test/tools/solfuzzer < crash.sol`

pull_request.title: Fix QueryJob total_rows attribute error
pull_request.body:
# Fix QueryJob total_rows attribute error ## Summary This PR fixes a critical `AttributeError` that occurs when the BigQuery API returns a `QueryJob` object without the `total_rows` attribute. The error `'QueryJob' object has no attribute 'total_rows'` was causing the application to crash when users asked questions like "how many republicans are there". **Root Cause:** The BigQuery `QueryJob` object doesn't always populate the `total_rows` attribute, particularly for certain query types (like COUNT queries) or under specific conditions. The code was attempting to access this attribute directly, causing an AttributeError. **Fix:** Changed from direct attribute access `query_job.total_rows` to safe access using `getattr(query_job, 'total_rows', None)`, which returns None if the attribute doesn't exist rather than raising an exception. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Critical**: Test end-to-end with actual BigQuery queries that return results (not just permission errors) to verify the fix works and doesn't break normal functionality - [ ] **High**: Verify truncation detection still works correctly when `total_rows` is available vs when it's None - [ ] **Medium**: Test various query types (SELECT, COUNT, aggregations, complex queries) to ensure consistent behavior across different BigQuery response patterns **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Run the agent CLI with COUNT queries: "how many republicans are there" 2. Run regular SELECT queries to ensure truncation detection still works 3. pull_request.body:
Synchronizes dearxan state in the entire process so that it only ever runs once, even accross multiple modules. Also lifts the restriction on `neuter_arxan` and `schedule_after_arxan` where calling them more than once would panic - callbacks are now queued in FIFO order.

Also refines the FFI structures and adds a C++ FFI to `include/dearxan.h`.
